abstract: A tech-savvy artist unearthed video footage of people working hard to capture the perfect shot for Instagram. It is a lesson in the artifice of social media and the ubiquity of surveillance.
snippet: A tech-savvy artist unearthed video footage of people working hard to capture the perfect shot for Instagram. It is a lesson in the artifice of social media and the ubiquity of surveillance.
lead_paragraph: David Welly Sombra Rodrigues, a 35-year-old French teacher, loves to travel. After the pandemic forced him to offer his language lessons virtually, he seized the moment, relocating from Brazil to Europe, where he could hop on trains to new cities to his heart’s delight, all of which he documented on Instagram.

main: This Surveillance Artist Knows How You Got That Perfect Instagram Photo
print_headline: Instagram Moments and a Surveillance Artist

abstract: Apocalyptic photographers, amnesiac killers and dueling Karen Gillans make up this month’s sci-fi selections.
snippet: Apocalyptic photographers, amnesiac killers and dueling Karen Gillans make up this month’s sci-fi selections.
lead_paragraph: Just a few minutes into this new South Korean import, it’s obvious we are in for a completely bonkers ride. Shortly after waking up with amnesia and a cross-shaped incision on the back of his neck, Carter (Joo Won, the star of the original Korean version of “The Good Doctor”) has recovered enough to brutally dispatch dozens of half-naked foes in a blood-soaked melee inside a bath house. He hears a woman’s voice in his head that informs him that a spreading virus is turning people into bald zombielike maniacs, and he must deliver the antidote to North Korea. Should Carter, a rogue former C.I.A. operative, trust a disembodied voice from North Korea to begin with? You have one guess.

main: Five Science Fiction Movies to Stream Now
print_headline: Snapping Pictures Like There’s No Tomorrow
